<TITLE> Banks hit European shares as rally fizzles out </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 LONDON, Feb 19 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - European equities fell in early trade on Tuesday, paring some of the previous day's 2 percent jump, as banks crowded the losers' list after Credit Suisse and Barclays reported further writedowns. Helping offset some of the losses in the market were BP and Total rose as oil prices edged up. By 0820 GMT, the pan-European FTSEurofirst 300 index was 0.3 percent weaker at 1,331.8. The index is down 12 percent so far this year, hit by US recession worries and a slump in banks awash with losses linked to a credit crunch. The DJ Stoxx European bank sector index lost 1.3 percent, with shares in Credit Suisse down 7.2 percent, Barclays shed 3.7 percent and UBS gave up 2.3 percent. Barclays reported pretax profits just ahead of average forecasts. "I think it'll be another tough day. The overall sentiment is bearish again, you can't trust these figures," said Mark Sartori, head of European equities at Fox-Pitt, Kelton. Asian stocks gained, boosted by exporters and banks, while US markets resume trading with results due from top retailer Wal-Mart Stores and Hewlett-Packa
